issue.title: Project logo
issue.body:
It would be great to get a logo for Ticketbooth. Something simple which can be used to identify the project.

It will be used as the icon displayed on GitHub. The icon will also be displayed as the page icon in the browser for the docs and eventual website, so should be designed for placement in modern browsers. This includes chromium-based browsers, safari and ideally also firefox and edge.

issue.title: Gas consumption improvements

milestone.title: V1.1
milestone.description: Gas improvements and smart contract optimisation

issue.body:
Lots of good ideas for gas consumption improvements were suggested on stratisproject/CirrusSmartContracts#8. Key improvements:

* Change Seat.Number data type to uint8 or uint16 (I'd lean towards using ushort, since byte could be too restrictive)
* Accept ordered array of prices instead of tickets on ```BeginSale```
* Accept array index, instead of seat, on ```Reserve``` and ```ReleaseTicket```

These changes could potentially roughly double the number of seats a contract could handle (and may be able to remove the arbitrary `MAX_SEATS` cap if constructor cost becomes greater than `BeginSale` cost).

issue.title: Scanner app does not filter previous sale ticket transactions
issue.body: The scanner app is not filtering transactions for a previous sale. This means that after 2 sales, checking a ticket could produce the wrong result. The scanner app needs to filter out previous sales, by getting the block number of the start of the sale and evaluating the block number of each ticket transaction.

issue.title: Favour password hashing over enciphering
issue.body: Using a hashing algortihm seems to be the standard approach to password encryption. Changing from AES to hashing could in theory increase security and should make management of passwords easier for a sales platform.

issue.title: Proper ticket ownership verification

milestone.title: MVP
milestone.description: A minimum product that can be showcased and used as a physical solution

issue.body:
Ticket ownership cannot be securely verified by providing an address, as anyone can look up transactions to the node to retrieve the address that tickets store. To solve this problem, a secret needs to be provided.

Since transaction data can be queried and viewed, the secret must be encrypted with symmetric encryption before the contract is called. A solution for this is to use AES, as the result string can be as short as 16 bytes and it is widely supported and used.
